Part 2

The second night, Vikram went out to the fire.

He told himself it was for a walk, the way people tell themselves things when they've already decided otherwise.

The Aghori didn't look up as he approached, didn't stop the motion of his hand — ash, Vikram saw now, up close, a handful lifted and let fall through his fingers, over and over, into a fire that didn't seem to need any more fuel than that.

"Sit if you're going to sit," the Aghori said. "Standing there is worse manners than sitting."

Vikram sat, at a distance that felt safe and probably wasn't.

"You run something," the Aghori said. Not a question.

"A company. My father's."

"Your father's." The Aghori repeated it the way a man repeats a mistake back to someone, gently, so they can hear it themselves. "Whose is it now?"

Vikram didn't answer that.

The Aghori let another handful of ash fall.

"Everything you're building," he said, "this will be. Doesn't mean don't build it."

---

He came back the third night, and didn't need to be told to sit.

"What is that," Vikram asked, nodding at the ash.

"A body. Somebody's body, once. Doesn't matter whose." The Aghori said it the way other men discussed the weather. "You people are frightened of this. I sit in it. Sleep in it, some nights. It stops being frightening once you understand it isn't waiting for you specially. It's just where everyone ends up."

"That's a bleak way to live."

"Is it." The Aghori looked at him for the first time properly, eyes catching the firelight in a way that made Vikram look away first. "Or is it the only honest way to live, and everything else is just very good decoration around the same fact?"

Vikram had no answer for that either, and the Aghori didn't seem to expect one.

---

By the fourth day, the Aghori had started appearing at the farmhouse itself, in daylight, sitting on the low wall outside the guest room as if he'd always been permitted there, which perhaps, in Ramanna's silent accounting, he had.

Ramanna brought him tea without being asked, the way you'd bring tea to an uncle who visits too rarely to be told to stop.

"Empty," the Aghori said one afternoon, apropos of nothing, watching Vikram read a stack of licensing papers.

"What is?"

"All of it. This—" he gestured at the papers, the farmhouse, the hills, with the same hand, "—it will pass. You will pass. The company will pass. Even this tea will be finished in a minute, and no one will remember it was ever hot."

"Then why bother with any of it?"

"I didn't say don't bother." The Aghori drank his tea, unhurried. "I said don't be surprised when it goes. Different thing entirely. A man who expects the tea to go cold still drinks it while it's hot. Only a fool sits waiting for it to stay warm forever, and calls that patience."

Vikram found himself, oddly, finishing the papers faster that day, and minding it less.

He didn't tell Reddy, when they spoke on the phone that evening, why his voice sounded calmer than it had in months.

He wasn't sure he could have explained it correctly even if he'd tried.
